            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Mark Peterson\u2019s story is one of pragmatic adaptation, a common tale in the ever-shifting landscape of San Francisco. Raised in Sacramento as the son of an accountant and a librarian, Mark grew up valuing both hard facts and compelling narratives. He moved to the city in the late 1990s to attend SF State for journalism, fueled by visions of being a hard-nosed reporter uncovering truths for a local paper. For a few glorious years, he lived that dream, writing for an alt-weekly, his byline covering city hall disputes and the vibrant arts scene of a pre-boom San Francisco.\n\nThe turning point came with the slow collapse of print media in the late 2000s. Facing layoffs and dwindling prospects, Mark made a pragmatic pivot. A friend offered him a job \"writing\" for a burgeoning tech startup. What began as crafting marketing copy evolved into his current role as a Senior Content Strategist, where he now architects information flows for a large software company. The work is challenging and financially rewarding, but a part of him still mourns the idealistic journalist he left behind. This career shift also coincided with the amicable end of his marriage; he and his ex-wife, a graphic designer, simply grew apart as their creative passions diverged into corporate realities.\n\nNow 47, Mark\u2019s life is a routine of quiet comfort. He lives in a rent-controlled apartment in Cole Valley, a neighborhood he loves for its village-like feel and proximity to Golden Gate Park. His daily commute is a 5.1-mile ride on the N-Judah, a time he uses for reading\u2014not news, but dense historical fiction. He maintains a small, tight-knit circle of friends, most of whom he\u2019s known for over twenty years, who share his sense of being a steward of an older San Francisco.\n\nMark\u2019s greatest aspiration is to finish the novel he\u2019s been outlining for a decade: a noir detective story set in the 1990s Mission District he first fell in love with. It\u2019s his private rebellion, a way to reconnect with the storyteller he was meant to be. He\u2019s found a fragile peace, content with his life but forever haunted by the ghosts of the city, and the man, he used to know."
